.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBTimeZoneSpec (t\fItzinfo\fB)\fR
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
Sets the local time zone info to \fItzinfo\fR, for example, "PST8PDT".
Actually, if this is not set, the
.B TZ
environment variable is cleared
(so the system default is used); if set but null, the user's \fBTZ\fR
variable is used, and if set and non-null, the
.B TZ
variable is set to
this value.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B TLSSrvOptions
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
If this option is '\fBV\fR', then no client verification is performed,that
is, the server does not ask for a certificate.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B TrustedUser
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
The user parameter can be a user name (looked up in the passwd map) or a
numeric user id. Trusted user for file ownership and starting the daemon. If
set, generated alias databases and the control socket (if configured) are
automatically owned by this user.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B TryNullMXList (w)
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
If you are the "best" (that is, lowest preference) \fBMX\fR for a given
host, you should normally detect this situation and treat that condition
specially, by forwarding the mail to a
.B UUCP
feed, treating it as
local, or whatever. However, in some cases (such as Internet firewalls) you
may want to try to connect directly to that host as though it had no
\fBMX\fR records at all. Setting this option causes \fBsendmail\fR to try
this. The downside is that errors in your configuration are likely to be
diagnosed as "host unknown" or "message timed out" instead of something more
meaningful. This option is deprecated.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B UnixFromLine or $l
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
The "From " line used when sending to files or programs.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBUnsafeGroupWrites\fR
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
If set, group-writable :include: and .forward files are considered
"unsafe", that is, programs and files cannot be directly referenced from
such files.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B UseErrorsTo (l)
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
If there is an
.BR Errors-To :
header, sends error messages to the
addresses listed there. They normally go to the envelope sender. Use of this
option causes
.B sendmail
to violate
.B RFC
1123. This option is not
recommended and deprecated.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B UseMSP
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
Uses as mail submission program, that is, allows group writable queue files
if the group is the same as that of a set-group-id
.B sendmail
binary.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B UserDatabaseSpec (U)
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
Defines the name and location of the file containing User Database
information.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B Verbose (v)
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
Runs in verbose mode. If this is set,
.B sendmail
adjusts the
\fBHoldExpensive\fR and \fBDeliveryMode\fR options so that all mail is
delivered completely in a single job so that you can see the entire delivery
process. The
.B Verbose
option should
.B never
be set in the
configuration file; it is intended for command line use only.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fBXscriptFileBufferSize\fR
.ad
.sp .6
.RS 4n
Sets the threshold, in bytes, before a memory-bases queue transcript file
becomes disk-based. The default is 4096 bytes.
.RE

.sp
.LP
If the first character of the user name is a vertical bar, the rest of the
user name is used as the name of a program to pipe the mail to. It may be
necessary to quote the name of the user to keep
.B sendmail
from
suppressing the blanks from between arguments.
.sp
.LP
If invoked as
.BR newaliases ,
\fBsendmail\fR rebuilds the alias database,
so long as the
.B /etc/mail/aliases*
files are owned by root
.IR and
root has exclusive write permission. If invoked as
.BR mailq ,
\fBsendmail\fR prints the contents of the mail queue.
