.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.sp
.LP
No environment variables are used. However, sendmail's start-up script,
invoked by
.BR svcadm "(1M), reads"
.BR /etc/default/sendmail .
In this
file, if the variable
.B ETRN_HOSTS
is set, the start-up script parses
this variable and invokes \fBetrn\fR(1M) appropriately. \fBETRN_HOSTS\fR
should be of the form:
.sp
.in +2
.nf
"s1:c1.1,c1.2        s2:c2.1 s3:c3.1,c3.2,c3.3"
.fi
.in -2
.sp

.sp
.LP
That is, white-space separated groups of
.I server:client
where
\fIclient\fR can be one or more comma-separated names. The \fI:client\fR
part is optional.
.I server
is the name of the server to prod; a mail
queue run is requested for each
.I client
name. This is comparable to
running:
.sp
.in +2
.nf
/usr/lib/sendmail -qR \fIclient\fR
.fi
.in -2
.sp

.sp
.LP
on the host
.IR server .
